Throughout the whole period of his residence in the capital he was a client, one of that numerous class of needy dependente who relied for their support solely upon the generosity of their patrous. It was not at any time a position of dignity, but in the case of Martial, who had no difficulty in securing the patronage of rich and influential citizens, it carried with it a fair competence, and afforded him boundless opportunities for coming in contact with those sides of Roman life which furnished the best material for the pen of the epigramma- tist.
